            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rajiv Kapoor\u2019s life is a testament to quiet, persistent dedication. Born in Fremont to Indian immigrants, his engineer father and librarian mother instilled in him a dual appreciation for systematic thinking and public service. While his peers in the booming 1980s Bay Area were drawn to Silicon Valley's allure, a teenage Rajiv found his calling during a volunteer creek cleanup project. He was fascinated by the tangible impact of coordinated effort on the local environment, a spark that would define his professional life.\n\nHe pursued a political science degree at UC Berkeley, followed by a Master of Public Administration from USC, intentionally choosing a path of civic duty over corporate profit. His career began with an entry-level analyst position in San Francisco\u2019s Department of the Environment. Over three decades, he methodically worked his way up, becoming a respected expert on waste reduction and water conservation policies. Now, as Deputy Director, he is the institutional memory of the department, the steady hand guiding ambitious projects through bureaucratic and political mazes.\n\nA key turning point was his divorce fifteen years ago. Amicable yet profound, it stemmed from a divergence in life goals with his then-wife, who favored a more financially driven path. The separation solidified Rajiv's commitment to his work, which became his primary focus. He maintains a warm, supportive relationship with his daughter, Priya, now an environmental science major at UC Davis, seeing his legacy live on through her.\n\nToday, Rajiv lives a structured life in his Hayes Valley condo. His day begins with the N-Judah Muni line, a 3.5-mile commute he uses for reading policy briefs. Evenings are for cooking simple meals, reading historical non-fiction, and weekly calls with Priya. His social circle is small but tight-knit, composed of colleagues and a few friends from a local hiking club. His greatest hope isn't personal promotion but seeing the city adopt a sweeping greywater recycling initiative he has championed for years. For Rajiv, San Francisco is not just a home; it is his life's work, a complex, fragile ecosystem he has dedicated himself to protecting, one policy at a time."
